  <Hero
    title="Stage 3: Active"
    subtitle="Inject. Observe. Verify."
    date="Lenora AI workflows · march 2026"
    codeComment="// Horus Daisy Chain — Stage 3"
  />

  <div class="container">
    <div class="card article">
      <h2>Origin</h2>
      <p>See <a href="/blog/specs/daisy-chains/horus-daisy-chain-stage-1-passive/#origin">stage 1 — passive</a> for the full hardware-to-DDD mapping. Stage 3 corresponds to <strong>point 8: progressive test extraction</strong> — the arc from functional test (Playwright E2E) → boundary scan vectors (direct injection) → ATPG (auto-generated specs from observed production traffic).</p>

      <hr>

      <h2>What is stage 3</h2>
      <p>Stage 1 watches passively. Stage 2 reacts to triggers and classifies outcomes. Stage 3 <strong>injects the trigger itself</strong> and verifies the system produces the expected outcome.</p>
      <p>This is the equivalent of applying test vectors to a hardware scan chain — you control the input, you know the expected output, and any deviation is a fault.</p>
      <p><strong>Requires stage 2.</strong> Active specs reuse reactive spec structure (trigger, outcomes, known_errors) but add an <code>inject</code> block and an <code>expected_outcome</code>.</p>

      <hr>

      <h2>Spec structure</h2>
      <pre>specs:
  &lt;name&gt;:
    mode: active
    inject:
      via: &lt;adapter&gt;
      method: &lt;HTTP method&gt;
      url: &lt;target URL&gt;
      body: &#123; ... &#125;
    timeout: &lt;duration&gt;
    expected_outcome: &lt;outcome_name&gt;
    outcomes:
      &lt;outcome_name&gt;:
        - service: ...
          signal: ...
      known_errors:
        &lt;error_name&gt;:
          - ...
    unknown_path: alert</pre>

      <ul>
        <li><strong><code>inject</code></strong> — DCME sends this signal to start the chain. This is the test vector.</li>
        <li><strong><code>expected_outcome</code></strong> — which outcome constitutes a "pass." If the system follows a different outcome, the test fails with a classification (not just a timeout).</li>
        <li><strong><code>outcomes</code></strong> and <strong><code>known_errors</code></strong> — identical to stage 2. The reactive matching engine runs the same way.</li>
      </ul>

      <hr>

      <h2>Progressive testing</h2>
      <p>Three phases, mirroring hardware's functional test → boundary scan extraction → ATPG:</p>

      <h3>Phase 1 — Playwright as test vector injector</h3>
      <p>Playwright drives the browser. DCME observes the full chain end-to-end. The Playwright test is minimal — click the button, DCME does all the verification.</p>
      <pre>specs:
  example_e2e:
    mode: active
    inject:
      via: playwright
      script: tests/e2e/submit-action.spec.ts
    timeout: 15s
    expected_outcome: completed
    outcomes:
      completed:
        - service: processor
          signal:
            direction: emit
            via: nats
            match:
              subject: "results.completed.*"
      rejected:
        - service: processor
          signal:
            direction: emit
            via: nats
            match:
              subject: "requests.rejected.*"
    unknown_path: alert</pre>

      <p>No assertions in Playwright. Playwright is dumb — it clicks. DCME is smart — it verifies.</p>

      <h3>Phase 2 — Direct injection</h3>
      <p>Strip Playwright. DCME injects the test vector directly via HTTP or NATS publish. No browser, no UI, no Playwright dependency.</p>
      <pre>specs:
  example_direct_http:
    mode: active
    inject:
      via: http
      method: POST
      url: http://$&#123;ENV&#125;.example.io/api/resource
      headers:
        Content-Type: application/json
        X-Test-Vector: "true"
      body:
        type: "test"
        correlationId: "TEST-$&#123;TIMESTAMP&#125;"
    timeout: 10s
    expected_outcome: completed
    outcomes:
      completed:
        - service: processor
          signal:
            direction: emit
            via: nats
            match:
              subject: "results.completed.*"
      rejected:
        - service: processor
          signal:
            direction: emit
            via: nats
            match:
              subject: "requests.rejected.*"
    unknown_path: alert</pre>

      <p>Can also inject via NATS directly:</p>
      <pre>specs:
  example_direct_nats:
    mode: active
    inject:
      via: nats
      subject: "requests.created.TEST"
      body:
        type: RequestCreated
        correlationId: "TEST-$&#123;TIMESTAMP&#125;"
    timeout: 10s
    expected_outcome: completed
    outcomes:
      # ... same as above</pre>

      <h3>Phase 3 — ATPG (future)</h3>
      <p>Automatic Test Pattern Generation. DCME observes production traffic (stage 1 + 2) and auto-generates active test specs from observed patterns.</p>
      <pre>observed: requests.created.* → results.completed.* (8ms) → notifications.sent.* (12ms)
         correlation: correlationId
         frequency: 340/hour
         p95 latency: 92ms

generated spec:
  example_learned:
    mode: active
    inject:
      via: nats
      subject: "requests.created.ATPG"
      body:
        type: RequestCreated
        correlationId: "ATPG-$&#123;TIMESTAMP&#125;"
        # body shape inferred from observed traffic
    timeout: 500ms  # derived from p95 + margin
    expected_outcome: completed
    outcomes:
      completed:
        # links auto-generated from observed chain</pre>

      <p>ATPG is the endgame: DCME writes its own tests from watching production.</p>

      <hr>

      <h2>Example: synthetic monitoring</h2>
      <p>Active specs can run on a schedule for health checking:</p>
      <pre>specs:
  health_check:
    mode: active
    inject:
      via: nats
      subject: "requests.created.HEALTHCHECK"
      body:
        type: RequestCreated
        correlationId: "HEALTH-$&#123;TIMESTAMP&#125;"
    timeout: 15s
    expected_outcome: completed
    schedule: every 5m

    outcomes:
      completed:
        - service: processor
          signal:
            direction: emit
            via: nats
            match:
              subject: "results.completed.*"
      known_errors:
        service_down:
          - service: processor
            signal:
              direction: emit
              via: nats
              match:
                subject: "requests.error.*"
                body.code: SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE
    unknown_path: alert</pre>

      <hr>

      <h2>Test result classification</h2>
      <p>For every active spec execution, DCME produces a result:</p>
      <table>
        <tr>
          <th>Result</th>
          <th>Meaning</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>pass</strong></td>
          <td>System followed <code>expected_outcome</code> within timeout</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>wrong_outcome</strong></td>
          <td>Chain completed but followed a different outcome than expected</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>known_error</strong></td>
          <td>Chain followed a <code>known_errors</code> path — expected failure</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>chain_break</strong></td>
          <td>Outcome partially matched — some links fired, then stopped</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>unknown_path</strong></td>
          <td>No outcome matched at all — undefined behavior</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>timeout</strong></td>
          <td>Nothing happened within timeout — system unresponsive</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>injection_failed</strong></td>
          <td>DCME couldn't send the test vector (HTTP error, NATS unreachable)</td>
        </tr>
      </table>

      <hr>

      <h2>Relationship to stages 1 and 2</h2>
      <p>All three stages can run simultaneously:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Stage 1 (passive)</strong> monitors every chain link-by-link in production.</li>
        <li><strong>Stage 2 (reactive)</strong> classifies real user triggers into outcomes.</li>
        <li><strong>Stage 3 (active)</strong> injects synthetic triggers and verifies expected outcomes.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Same matching engine, same adapters, same scan cells. The only difference is who initiates the trigger:</p>
      <table>
        <tr>
          <th>Stage</th>
          <th>Trigger source</th>
          <th>Question</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>1 — passive</td>
          <td>nobody</td>
          <td>"Did every link fire in order?"</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>2 — reactive</td>
          <td>real traffic</td>
          <td>"Given this trigger, which outcome?"</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>3 — active</td>
          <td>DCME injects</td>
          <td>"If I inject this, do I get the expected outcome?"</td>
        </tr>
      </table>

      <hr>

      <h2>v0.2 roadmap</h2>

      <h3>Agent adapter</h3>
      <p>Claude Code as a chain link for active test specs. Agent can be both an injector (creating test scenarios) and a gate (making decisions within a chain).</p>

      <h3>FIX protocol adapter</h3>
      <p>FIX session observer and injector for counterparty chain testing (e.g., Bond Port integration).</p>

      <h3>ATPG engine</h3>
      <p>DCME learns chain specs from observed production traffic and auto-generates active test specs. Derived from stage 1 and 2 observation data.</p>

      <h3>Schedule and CI integration</h3>
      <p>Active specs runnable on a cron schedule (synthetic monitoring) or triggered from CI/CD pipelines. Test results reported as standard test output (JUnit XML, TAP, etc.).</p>
